+/* MP6 native port -- BE fixup + 32-on-64-bit pointer relayout.
+ * See docs/M2A_ENDIANNESS.md. Two independent problems live in this one
+ * chokepoint:
+ *
+ * 1. Every multi-byte field in the packed ANIM blob (produced by the
+ *    original big-endian PowerPC toolchain) is big-endian; a plain
+ *    struct-member read on this little-endian host reads it byte-swapped.
+ * 2. ANIMDATA/ANIMBANK/ANIMPAT/ANIMBMP each embed one or more real
+ *    pointer-typed fields (bank/pat/bmp, frame, layer, palData/data).
+ *    Those fields are 4 bytes on the original 32-bit target but 8 bytes in
+ *    this native 64-bit build (docs/PLAN.md A1), so the record STRIDES
+ *    differ from what the packed blob actually contains -- walking this
+ *    data through the native struct types in place (as the original code
+ *    did, relying on real hardware's matching 32-bit ABI) reads the wrong
+ *    bytes entirely, a separate bug from pure byte order.
+ *
+ * Fixed by treating `data` as an opaque byte blob laid out per the
+ * ORIGINAL (32-bit, big-endian) ANIM format -- read explicitly via be16()/
+ * be32() at the format's fixed byte offsets -- and building a fresh,
+ * natively-laid-out ANIMDATA/ANIMBANK/ANIMPAT/ANIMBMP/ANIMFRAME/ANIMLAYER
+ * graph from it in one new allocation. ANIMFRAME and ANIMLAYER contain no
+ * pointer fields, so their native layout already matches the packed
+ * layout byte-for-byte; only their s16 fields need swapping. Raw texture/
+ * palette PIXEL bytes (ANIMBMP.data/.palData) are deliberately NOT copied
+ * or byte-swapped -- they stay exactly where the decoder put them and are
+ * consumed as opaque GameCube-native tiled/paletted texture data
+ * (docs/PLAN.md A3 point 1); only the CPU-parsed container fields above
+ * them are converted here.
+ *
+ * A small side-table cache (mirroring platform/os/dll_bridge.c's own
+ * open-file side table) reproduces the original's "already fixed up,
+ * just bump the refcount" fast path -- the original detected that case by
+ * testing the high bits of the still-packed `bank` OFFSET against a real
+ * pointer's high bits, a test that doesn't transfer once fixed-up data no
+ * longer lives at the same address as its own packed source. */
+/* M3 (docs/M3_HSF.md), round 3: 64 was already tight for a full boot's
+ worth of ANIM objects (79 character anims alone in one opening.c loop);
+ the two self-registration fixes above double the fill rate (each
+ HuSprAnimRead/HuSprAnimMake call can now add TWO entries, input and
+ output identity, instead of one). A linear scan over a few thousand
+ pointer-sized slots costs nothing measurable at this call frequency
+ (load-time, not per-frame), so there's no real downside to a generous
+ budget here. */
+#define MP6_ANIM_CACHE_MAX 4096
+static struct { void *rawData; ANIMDATA *anim; u32 fingerprint; } mp6_animCache[MP6_ANIM_CACHE_MAX];
+
+/* MP6 native port -- B2 (docs/B2_BONUS_SPRITE.md). The cache above assumes
+ * a cached entry's key address can only be reused once HuSprAnimKill has
+ * removed it (mp6_animCacheRemove, below) -- true for per-object teardown,
+ * but NOT for the engine's own BULK, tag-based frees (game/objmain.c /
+ * REL/bootDll/boot.c: `HuMemDirectFreeNum(HEAP_MODEL, HU_MEMNUM_OVL)`,
+ * fired wholesale on every overlay transition). That call reclaims a whole
+ * heap region in one shot without walking individual objects, so it never
+ * runs HuSprAnimKill/mp6_animCacheRemove for anything it frees -- every
+ * mp6_animCache entry keyed by an address inside that region survives,
+ * silently describing memory that no longer holds what it used to. The
+ * NEXT overlay's own HuDataSelHeapReadNum calls are free to reuse those
+ * same addresses. Confirmed concretely: Party Mode's mdpartydll loads 41
+ * same-shaped icon ANIM files into freshly decompressed HU_MEMNUM_OVL/
+ * HEAP_MODEL buffers, and the Bonus Star with/without-bonus icon (dataNo
+ * 36/37, `data/mdparty.bin` file 0x49/0x4A, genuinely 128x128 CI8/GX_TF_C8
+ * with a 160-entry RGB5A3 TLUT -- confirmed via tools/gc_tex_decode.py
+ * against the disc file's own offline-decompressed bytes, which decode to
+ * a clean "With Bonus"/"Without Bonus" hexagon) landed on an address a
+ * stale entry from an earlier overlay's own icon table still claimed.
+ * mp6_animCacheFind then returned that stale, unrelated ANIMDATA (a
+ * genuinely RGB565-format icon: dataFmt=1, palNum=0) instead of parsing
+ * the fresh, correct C8 bytes -- and because its own bmp->data/palData
+ * were computed relative to ITS OWN (also address-reused) raw buffer, they
+ * still resolved INTO the new resource's real pixel data, just at the old
+ * asset's relative offset (+0x80, the true palOff, instead of the correct
+ * +0x1C0 dataOff) -- so the port read real C8 index bytes as RGB5A3 color
+ * pairs (a smeared top) and then overran 16KB past the resource's own
+ * pixel data into whatever followed (pure noise below): exactly the
+ * reported "jumble of colored blocks". MP6_DECODE_GUARD proved the live
+ * zlib decompress (decodeType 7) produced byte-identical output to the
+ * offline reference (checksum match); MP6_DRAW_CENSUS_OBJ caught the live
+ * parse's dataFmt=1/palNum=0/data==palData red-handed -- decompression and
+ * the parsing FORMULAS are both innocent; only a stale cache HIT explains
+ * a correct buffer's bytes being described by someone else's format.
